ğŸ’¡ Step-by-Step How IoC Works Here
1ï¸âƒ£ Model Layer
package com.example.userregistration.model;

public class User {
    private String name;
    private String email;

    // constructor, getters, setters
}

2ï¸âƒ£ Repository Layer
package com.example.userregistration.repository;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;
import com.example.userregistration.model.User;

@Repository  // ğŸ‘ˆ Tells Spring: "Make an object of this class"
public class UserRepository {
    public void save(User user) {
        System.out.println("Saving user to database: " + user.getName());
    }
}


âœ… When the app starts, Spring scans your code and sees @Repository.
ğŸ‘‰ It automatically creates an object (bean) of UserRepository.

3ï¸âƒ£ Service Layer
package com.example.userregistration.service;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import com.example.userregistration.model.User;
import com.example.userregistration.repository.UserRepository;

@Service  // ğŸ‘ˆ Another bean created by Spring
public class UserService {

    private final UserRepository userRepository;

    @Autowired  // ğŸ‘ˆ Spring will inject the UserRepository object here
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }

    public void registerUser(String name, String email) {
        User user = new User();
        user.setName(name);
        user.setEmail(email);
        userRepository.save(user);
    }
}


âœ… Spring creates UserService.
âœ… It automatically inserts the UserRepository bean inside it (thatâ€™s IoC in action ğŸ’¥).

4ï¸âƒ£ Controller Layer (Handles Website Requests)
package com.example.userregistration.controller;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import com.example.userregistration.service.UserService;

@RestController  // ğŸ‘ˆ Marks it as a web controller (also a bean)
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    private final UserService userService;

    @Autowired  // ğŸ‘ˆ Spring injects the UserService bean here
    public UserController(UserService userService) {
        this.userService = userService;
    }

    @PostMapping("/register")
    public String registerUser(@RequestParam String name, @RequestParam String email) {
        userService.registerUser(name, email);
        return "User registered successfully!";
    }
}


âœ… Spring creates UserController.
âœ… It automatically injects the UserService object into it.

5ï¸âƒ£ Main Application Class
package com.example.userregistration;

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

@SpringBootApplication  // ğŸ‘ˆ enables component scanning & IoC container
public class UserRegistrationApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(UserRegistrationApplication.class, args);
    }
}


âœ… This starts the Spring IoC container (ApplicationContext).
âœ… It scans all packages for @Controller, @Service, @Repository etc.
âœ… Creates objects (beans).
âœ… Connects them together automatically.

âš¡ How It Works When You Open the Website

1ï¸âƒ£ User hits the API endpoint:

POST http://localhost:8080/users/register?name=Alice&email=alice@gmail.com


2ï¸âƒ£ Spring finds the UserController â†’ itâ€™s already created by IoC.
3ï¸âƒ£ UserController calls UserService â†’ IoC already injected it.
4ï¸âƒ£ UserService calls UserRepository â†’ IoC already injected it.
5ï¸âƒ£ UserRepository saves the data (prints output).

ğŸª„ You never used new anywhere.
Spring created and connected everything for you.

ğŸ§  Behind the Scenes (IoC Flow)
SpringApplication.run(...) â†’ starts IoC container
      â†“
Scans all packages for @Component, @Service, @Repository, @Controller
      â†“
Creates objects (beans)
      â†“
Finds dependencies marked with @Autowired
      â†“
Injects the right beans into each other
      â†“
App is ready to handle requests ğŸš€

ğŸ§© Output Example (Console)

